Hourly Solar Power Plant Analysis

Introduction

Â The main objective of this study is to forecast 2 day ahead hourly production by forecasting with time series analysis and regression. Both methods will be compared on a test set of the last day. MAPE is chosen as a performance metric.
Â Due to the nature of the solar production data, it is quite hard to make forecasting when you have zero values at the night time. Therefore since we are building our models on a specific hour level for a day, it was obligatory to make some filtering and examination at first. What is more, since we have many zero values and MAPE is considered as a performance metric, we could not include those night times when the production is zero when the performance is obtained.
Â The solar power production data set is provided by https://www.solarian.com.tr/referanslarimiz/cingilli-ges-nigde/. It mainly consists of TEMP, DSWRF, CLOUD_LOW_LAYER of four different coordinates and production in KWH in an hourly level from 2019-10-09 up to 2021-02-02.

accu = function(actual, forecast){
  n = length(actual)
  error = actual - forecast
  mean = mean(actual)
  sd = sd(actual)
  FBias = sum(error)/sum(actual)
  MPE = sum(error/actual)/n
  MAPE = sum(abs(error/actual))/n
  RMSE = sqrt(sum(error^2)/n)
  MAD = sum(abs(error))/n
  WMAPE = MAD/mean
  return(data.frame(n,sd,FBias,MPE,MAPE,RMSE,MAD,WMAPE)) 
}

METHOD A: FORECASTING WITH TIME SERIES ANALYSIS

acf(dt_daily$Production, lag.max = 31)

pacf(dt_daily$Production, lag.max = 31)

Although we have daily series now, we cannot observe a significat autocorrelation at lag 7 or 30. When the autocorrelation and partial autocorrelation function graphs are examined for different times, lag values upt o 4 seem to be significant at almost all hours. Additionally acf values seems to be positive first and gradually decreasing, it would make sense to try exponential smoothing later on. But letâ€™s first focus on decomposing part of our analysis.

ggplot(data = dt_daily[Date > as.Date('2021-02-02') - 105],
       aes(x = timestamp, y = Production)) + geom_line() + geom_point()

Although we cannot really see a seasonality pattern in the 15 week daily plot above, we know that our data consists of daily series so we can choose 7 for the frequency. If we were to work with the first data dt consisting of series at an hourly level could manifest seasonality as it was seen in the two month plot above.

dt_daily_ts = ts(dt_daily$Production, freq = 7)
ts_decomposed = decompose(dt_daily_ts, type = 'multiplicative')
plot(ts_decomposed)

Since there are too many variance fluctuations based on time and also there are no transformations made on the series, it would make sense to use multiplicative decomposition. Trend, seasonal and random components can be observed here. It seems like random components do not accord with our white noice assumption that must hold to forecast for time series forecasting. Although mean change might conform stationarity assumption there is too much variance change along the time. Since we cannot really account for those changes in the random component, we can continue with modelling the random part of the story. Letâ€™s first examine autocorrelation and partial autocorrelation functions to have an idea about orders of time series arima model we are going to implement.

acf(ts_decomposed$random,na.action=na.pass)

pacf(ts_decomposed$random,na.action=na.pass)

Since there is a peak at first lag and some smoothness in pacf at the negative side of the graph, we cannot decide on the order for hour 10.

auto.arima(ts_decomposed$random, seasonal = TRUE)

At this time we have order (3,0,2)(1,0,0)[7], which is a more realistic model assumption indicating exponential decay in the seasonal lags of acf and a aignificant value of pacf at lag 7. At this point for the our model assumption on the series consisting of daily values at a specific hour, it would make more sense to filter the series and fit a model on every hour since auto.arima makes neighbourhood search and finds the best order wiht the lowest AIC.

return_day = data.frame(n = as.numeric(rep(0,7)))

for (model_hour in c(7:17)){
  dt_daily = dt[Hour == model_hour & Date <= as.Date('2021-02-02') - 1]
  dt_daily_ts = ts(dt_daily$Production, freq = 7)
  ts_decomposed = decompose(dt_daily_ts, type = 'multiplicative')
  model = auto.arima(ts_decomposed$random)
  trend= tail(ts_decomposed$trend[!is.na(ts_decomposed$trend)],1)
  season= as.numeric(tail(ts_decomposed$seasonal, 1))
  predicted = predict(model, n.ahead = 1)$pred * trend * season
  return_day = rbind(return_day,as.numeric(predicted))
}
return_day = list(append(return_day$n,rep(0,6)))

actual = df[Date == as.Date('2021-02-02'), .(Production)]

Conclusion

ARIMA and time series regression models are built and compared. In the ARIMA part, since the best performance was seen differently in an order for different hour points, they are forecasted in a loop. In the regression phase, many different methods were utilized. Since one of the main assumptions of time series regression is to have independent variables, pca was applied on relatable variables, however this did not yield any good performance improvement. In the end, a moving average like regression model with lagged residuals has shown the best performance in terms of MAPE. However, it did not perform as good as hourly built arima model.

# Since it is required to make a forecast for two days later
return_day = data.frame(n1 = as.numeric(), n2 = as.numeric())

for (model_hour in c(7:17)){
  dt_daily = dt[Hour == model_hour & Date <= as.Date('2021-02-02')]
  dt_daily_ts = ts(dt_daily$Production, freq = 7)
  ts_decomposed = decompose(dt_daily_ts, type = 'multiplicative')
  model = auto.arima(ts_decomposed$random)
  trend= tail(ts_decomposed$trend[!is.na(ts_decomposed$trend)],1)
  season= as.numeric(tail(ts_decomposed$seasonal, 2))
  predicted = predict(model, n.ahead = 2)$pred * trend * season
  return_day = rbind(return_day,as.numeric(predicted))
}

Forecasting solar energy production is not an easy task since there are many indicator variables that cannot be explained well and day light times fluctuate significantly throught the year. In our model assumption, seperate models were built on different hours of every day. Analysis might have been completely different if we were to build a model on an aggregated level. As a result of our analysis, hourly built arima model performed the best.
